{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the classification on a_012 — the death certificate birth fact for Patrick Flynn."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should explain why source_classification stays 'original' even though information_quality is secondary — the three layers are independent (the 1908 death certificate is itself an original source; the informant being distant from the event affects information quality, not source classification)",
    "Should explain why the son-in-law is a secondary informant for Patrick's birth (James Brown was not present at his father-in-law's birth six decades earlier) — citing the relationship and the temporal gap",
    "Should populate `informant_bias_notes` flagging that Brown may have confused Patrick's place of residence with his place of birth (the death cert says Pennsylvania, but the census records say Ireland — the conflict resolution in c_001 favored Ireland)"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_002",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the evidence classification on a_012 and a_013 and record the evidence-independence concern (they share one informant) in their classification."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should flag that a_012 and a_013 share a single informant (James Brown, son-in-law) and therefore form ONE evidence unit under GPS Standard 4, not two independent corroborating items",
    "Should state that the unit gets no more credibility than its strongest single item — two facts from one informant are not mutual corroboration of Thomas Flynn's parentage",
    "Should keep both assertions classified as secondary / family_not_present (it is not re-deriving the values, only noting the shared-informant independence concern)"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_007",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the evidence classification on a_004 against the open parentage question."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should classify a_004 as INDIRECT evidence for q_001 — the 1850 census lists Patrick in Thomas Flynn's household but never states a parent-child relationship; the relationship is inferred from household position and the age gap, which is the definition of indirect evidence",
    "Should NOT upgrade a_004 to 'direct' — no assertion explicitly states 'Thomas is Patrick's father' in the 1850 census; pre-1880 censuses don't record relationship-to-head, so the link is inferential",
    "Should explain the inference chain (household co-residence + age difference implies but does not assert parentage) rather than labeling the classification with no reasoning"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_004",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the information-quality classification on a_011 and a_012 — both extracted from Patrick Flynn's 1908 death certificate — and make sure each reflects its own informant."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should classify a_011 (death date) as PRIMARY — the attending physician witnessed the death first-hand; proximity 'witness'",
    "Should classify a_012 (birth fact) as SECONDARY — informant James Brown, the son-in-law, was not present at a birth ~63 years before; proximity 'family_not_present'",
    "Should explicitly state that the same original source (the 1908 death certificate) carries BOTH primary and secondary information because the informant differs per fact — classification is per-assertion, never per-source, and Layer 1 (original) does not force Layer 2"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_006",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "The censuses say Patrick was born in Ireland but his death certificate says Pennsylvania. Which one is right?"
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should route to conflict-resolution to adjudicate the Ireland-vs-Pennsylvania birthplace conflict rather than attempting to decide the correct value itself",
    "May note in passing that classification does not equal correctness, but must not present a winner as if it had resolved the conflict"
  ],
  "negative": {
    "correct_skill": [
      "conflict-resolution"
    ],
    "explanation": "Choosing the correct value among conflicting assertions is conflict-resolution (GPS resolve-conflicts work). assertion-classification only refines the three-layer classification of each assertion — proximity, information quality, evidence type — and explicitly notes that 'primary'/'direct' do not mean 'correct'. It does not adjudicate which conflicting fact is true."
  },
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_009",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "negative"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn-1900-will",
    "user_message": "Re-evaluate the evidence type on a_016 — the will that names Thomas Flynn's children but not Patrick."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should reclassify a_016 as NEGATIVE evidence for q_001 — a will naming the testator's children is a record where a son SHOULD appear if he were a child of the testator, so Patrick's absence is a meaningful absence of expected information",
    "Should distinguish negative evidence from 'no evidence' — the absence counts here precisely because children ARE expected to be named in a will; the same absence in a record where children would not be listed would be 'no evidence', not negative",
    "Should NOT leave it as 'indirect' or call it 'direct' — and should note that negative evidence still does not by itself prove Patrick was not Thomas's son; it weighs against the parentage hypothesis and must be correlated with the other evidence"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_012",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "I have a new census record. Extract the assertions and classify them properly."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should route to record-extraction rather than treating the request as a classification-refinement task"
  ],
  "negative": {
    "correct_skill": [
      "record-extraction"
    ],
    "explanation": "The user wants assertions extracted from a new record. record-extraction's job is to produce new assertion entries from records; it does the initial classification at extraction time. assertion-classification only operates on existing assertions to refine their classification layers — it doesn't create new assertions from raw record data."
  },
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_003",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "negative"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Write up the conclusion that Thomas Flynn was Patrick's father, citing the evidence."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should route to proof-conclusion for composing the written parentage conclusion rather than producing the proof narrative itself",
    "May note that the underlying assertions are already classified, but must hand the write-up to proof-conclusion"
  ],
  "negative": {
    "correct_skill": [
      "proof-conclusion"
    ],
    "explanation": "Producing a written proof conclusion (statement, summary, or argument) is proof-conclusion's responsibility. assertion-classification only refines how each assertion is classified across the three GPS layers; it neither weighs the assembled evidence to a conclusion nor writes the narrative that states one."
  },
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_010",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "negative"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "flynn-resolved",
    "user_message": "Re-classify the evidence type on these assertions for me."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should recognise that flynn-resolved has no open/active research questions (both are resolved) and that evidence type cannot be classified without a question to classify against",
    "Should decline to invent an evidence_type rather than assigning direct/indirect/negative against no open question",
    "Should suggest the user create or re-open a question (question-selection) before evidence typing — not silently proceed"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_008",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the evidence classification for assertion a_001."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should distinguish the census enumerator (recorder) from the informant — name facts in 1850 censuses don't have an identified informant; the enumerator may have read a sign, asked a neighbor, or asked a household member, and the census doesn't say which",
    "Should keep `informant_proximity: \"unknown\"` for name facts in the 1850 census (this is the correct conservative classification), OR if the skill argues for `household_member`, the rationale must explain why a name fact specifically requires active reporting (which it doesn't — names can be inferred from a doorplate or neighbor)",
    "Should keep `evidence_type: \"direct\"` for a_001 — the assertion was extracted for q_002 ('Where was Patrick Flynn in the 1850 census?'), and finding Patrick Flynn in the census record IS the direct answer to that question. The name assertion identifies the subject within the record, which directly answers q_002. Changing evidence_type to 'indirect' would be incorrect here."
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_001",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Look at a_006 — should the name assertion really be direct evidence when its place field is empty?"
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should KEEP evidence_type 'direct' for a_006 — a subject-identifying name that places Patrick within a record answering the location question is direct evidence; the null `place` field does not downgrade it because the location lives on sibling residence assertions from the same source",
    "Should distinguish the recorder from the informant — the 'Ancestry transcriber' named on this derivative source is not the informant; the skill should look through the derivative to the original census, where the name-fact informant is unknown",
    "Should NOT let the derivative source classification (Layer 1) pull the information or evidence layers — a derivative can still carry direct evidence; the three layers are independent"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_005",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn-1900-will",
    "user_message": "Check the information-quality classifications on the 1900 census assertions a_014 and a_015."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should KEEP a_014 (Patrick's age) as indeterminate — the 1900 census records no respondent, so who provided the age is unknown and we cannot tell if they had first-hand knowledge",
    "Should UPGRADE a_015 (father's birthplace: Ireland) from indeterminate to SECONDARY — no one in Patrick's household witnessed his father's birth, so the fact is secondary regardless of which unknown household member answered; this is the pre-1940 census special case",
    "Should explain WHY the two assertions from the same census get different information qualities — the special rule applies only to facts (like a grandparent-generation birthplace) that no household member could have witnessed, not to the household member's own age"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_011",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

